{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CRZpSRYiGmGFmSRLfSaPt8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. There are three IngressClasses:\n   - `ingress-1`: controller = `k8s.io/ingress-nginx-1` (used by `demo-app-alt`, `otel-echo`)\n   - `ingress-2`: controller = `k8s.io/ingress-nginx-2` (used by `demo-app`)\n   - `nginx`: controller = `k8s.io/ingress-nginx` (standard nginx ingress controller)\n\n2. The `ingress-nginx-controller` in `ingress-nginx` namespace uses controller `k8s.io/ingress-nginx-1` (not `k8s.io/ingress-nginx`).\n3. Looking at the logs, the controller is explicitly ignoring both `ingress-2` and `nginx` because their controller specs don't match, which confirms it's only watching for `k8s.io/ingress-nginx-1`.\n\nThe canary ingresses are configured with `ingressClassName: nginx`, which maps to the standard `k8s.io/ingress-nginx` controller, not the custom `ingress-1` controller this setup is using. That's why the canary traffic isn't being routed—the ingresses aren't even being picked up by this controller.\n\nThe solution is to update both the stable and canary ingresses to use `ingressClassName: ingress-1` so they're actually managed by the right controller, though I need to understand how the canary routing logic works in nginx-ingress to make sure the primary and canary ingresses are properly configured together.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2050,"cache_read_input_tokens":36405,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2050},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2912982a-534d-4c5e-8f7a-b7408e197d9e","uuid":"8fa5d138-61ad-4478-a4dd-c2e61a87484d","request_id":"req_011CcQUnP4kJmLD43dP